text: Nasolabial Fold Elevation with nasolabial fold elevation.
context: Left midface elevation with nasolabial fold elevation and nasolabial fold z-plasty and right symmetrization midface elevation.

text: Left nasolabial fold scar deformity with effacement of alar crease.
context: Left nasolabial fold scar deformity with effacement of alar crease.

text: Left nasolabial fold scar deformity with effacement of alar crease.
context: Left nasolabial fold scar deformity with effacement of alar crease.

text: Left nasolabial fold z-plasty and right symmetrization midface elevation.
context: Left midface elevation with nasolabial fold elevation and nasolabial fold z-plasty and right symmetrization midface elevation.

text: Blood loss
context: Estimated blood loss Less than 25 mL.

text: Implants
context: Coapt Endotine Midface B 4.5 bioabsorbable implants, reference #CFD0200197, lot #01447 used on the right and used on the left side

text: Patient consented for procedure
context: The patient was seen in consultation and felt to be a surgical candidate for improvement. Risks and benefits of the operation were described to the patient in detail including, but not limited to bleeding, infection, scarring, possible damage to surrounding structures including neurovascular structures, need for revision of surgery, continued asymmetry, and anesthetic complication. The patient understood these risks and benefits and consented to the operation.

text: supine on the operating table
context:
The patient was taken to OR and placed supine on the operating table.
the patient was turned 180 degrees

text: Antibiotics
context: Dose of antibiotics was given to the patient.

text: Compression devices placed
context: Compression devices were placed on the lower extremities to prevent the knee embolic events.

text: General endotracheal intubation.
context: General endotracheal intubation.

text: Drapes
context: area was then prepped and draped in usual sterile fashion. A head wrap was then placed on the position and we then began our local.

text: previous incisions just lateral to his lateral canthus
context: Of note, the patient had previous incisions just lateral to his lateral canthus bilaterally and that were used for access.

text: Local injected into the subperiosteal plane
context: Local consisting a 50:50 mix of 0.25% Marcaine with epinephrine and 1% lidocaine with epinephrine was then injected into the subperiosteal plane taking care to prevent injury to the infraorbital nerves. This was done bilaterally.

text: Nasolabial fold marked
context: We then marked the nasolabial fold and began with the elevation of the left midface.

text: Incision down through subcutaneous tissue to the periosteum
context: We began with a lateral canthal-type incision extending out over his previous incision down to subcutaneous tissue. We continued down to the lateral orbital rim until we identified periosteum.

text: Periosteal elevator used to elevate the midface
context: We then pulled in a periosteal elevator and elevated the midface down over the zygoma elevating some lateral mesenteric attachments down over the buccal region until we felt we had reached pass the nasolabial folds medially.

text: infraorbital nerve visualised during elevation
context: Care was taken to preserve the infraorbital nerve and that was visualized after elevation.

text: Endotine Coapt device to engage the periosteum
context: We then used our Endotine Coapt device to engage the periosteum at the desired location and then elevated the midface and secured into position using the Coapt bioabsorbable screw.

text: Coapt bioabsorbable screw to secure the elevation
context: We then used our Endotine Coapt device to engage the periosteum at the desired location and then elevated the midface and secured into position using the Coapt bioabsorbable screw.  After this was then carried out, we then clipped and cut as well as the end of the screw.

text: 3-0 monocryl used to secure the elevation
context: Satisfied with this, we then elevated the periosteum and secured it to reinforce our midface elevation to the lateral orbital rim and this was done using 3-0 Monocryl.

text: Sutures to anchor the orbicularis and deeper tissue
context: Several sutures were then used to anchor the orbicularis and deeper tissue to create additional symmetry.

text: Excess skin removed
context: Excess skin along the incision was then removed as well the skin from just lateral to the canthus.

text: orbicularismuscle was left down
context: Care was taken to leave the orbicularis muscle down.

text: 5-0 sutures for the subcillary type incision
context: We then continued closing our incision using absorbable plain gut 5-0 sutures for the subciliary-type incision

text: 6-0 prolene used
context: then continuing with interrupted 6-0 Prolenes lateral to the canthus.

text: 15 blade used to make the z-plasty incision
context:
designed along the previous scar where it was padding to the notable scar deformity and effacement of crease and the z-plasty was then designed to lengthen along the scar to improve the contour. This was carried out using a 15 blade down to subcutaneous tissue.
We carried this down to the lateral orbital rim again elevating the periosteum taking care to preserve infraorbital nerve.

text: Flaps were debulked slightly
context: The flaps were debulked slightly to reduce the amount of fullness and then transposed and sutured into place using chromic suture.

text: Asymmetry between left and right midface and nasolabial folds
context: At this point, we then noted that he had improvement of the nasal fold but continued asymmetry with regards to improved bulk on the left side and less bulk on the right and it was felt that a symmetrization procedure was required to make more symmetry with the midface bilaterally and nasolabial folds bilaterally.

text: periosteum released distally
context: At this point, we then released the periosteum distally just at the level of the nasolabial fold

text: Endotine midface implant inserted
context: placed our Endotine midface implant into the desired area and then elevated slightly just for symmetry only.

text: Endotine implant secured with bioabsorbable screw
context: Endotine midface implant into the desired area and then elevated slightly just for symmetry only. This was then secured in place using the bioabsorbable screw

text: Minimal amount of marginal tissue removed
context: then resected a very marginal amount of tissue just for removal of the dog ear deformity

text: 3-0 PDS used to close the deep layers
context: closed the deeper layers of tissue using 3-0 PDS

text: 5-0 plain gut to close the subcillary area
context: closed the deeper layers of tissue using 3-0 PDS and then closing the extension to the subciliary area using 5-0 plain gut and then 6-0 Prolene lateral to the canthus.

text: 6-0 prolene to close lateral to the canthus
context: closed the deeper layers of tissue using 3-0 PDS and then closing the extension to the subciliary area using 5-0 plain gut and then 6-0 Prolene lateral to the canthus.

text: Post procedure patient had improved contour, symmetry and decreased effacement
context: At this point, we felt that we had achieved improved contour, improved symmetry, and decreased effacement of the nasolabial fold and alar crease.

text: Cool compress placed on to the eyes
context: Satisfied with our procedures, we then placed cool compresses on to the eyes.

text: Patient brought to PACU post procedure
context: The patient was then extubated and brought to the PACU in stable condition.

text: Dr X actively participated during all key elements
context: Dr. X was present and scrubbed for the entire case and actively participated during all key elements

text: Dr Y was available and participated in portions of the procedure
context: Dr. Y was available and participated in the portions of the case as well.
